topics.body_text:
In previous sections, we have evaluated the trigonometric functions at various angles, but at times we need to know what angle would yield a specific sine, cosine, or tangent value. For this, we need inverse functions. Recall that for a one-to-one function, if \(f(a)=b\), then an inverse function would satisfy \(f^{-1} (b)=a\). You probably are already recognizing an issue – that the sine, cosine, and tangent functions are not one-to-one functions. To define an inverse of these functions, we will need to restrict the domain of these functions to yield a new function that is one-to-one. We choose a domain for each function that includes the angle zero. On these restricted domains, we can define the inverse sine, inverse cosine, and inverse tangent functions. INVERSE SINE, COSINE, AND TANGENT FUNCTIONS and their inverses For angles in the interval \(\left[-\dfrac{\pi }{2} ,\dfrac{\pi }{2} ight]\), if \(\sin \left(	heta ight)=a\), then \(\sin ^{-1} \left(aight)=	heta\) \(\sin ^{-1} \left(xight)\) has domain [-1, 1] and range \(\left[-\dfrac{\pi }{2} ,\dfrac{\pi }{2} ight]\) The \(\sin ^{-1} \left(xight)\) is sometimes called the arcsine function, and notated \(\arcsin \left(aight)\). For angles in the interval \(\left[0,\pi ight]\), if \(\cos \left(	heta ight)=a\), then \(\cos ^{-1} \left(aight)=	heta\) \(\cos ^{-1} \left(xight)\) has domain [-1, 1] and range \(\left[0,\pi ight]\) The \(\cos ^{-1} \left(xight)\) is sometimes called the arccosine function, and notated \(\arccos \left(aight)\). For angles in the interval \(\left(-\dfrac{\pi }{2} ,\dfrac{\pi }{2} ight)\), if \(	an \left(	heta ight)=a\), then \(	an ^{-1} \left(aight)=	heta\) \(	an ^{-1} \left(xight)\) has domain of all real numbers and range \(\left(-\dfrac{\pi }{2} ,\dfrac{\pi }{2} ight)\) The \(	an ^{-1} \left(xight)\) is sometimes called the arctangent function, and notated \(\arctan \left(aight)\). The graphs of the inverse functions are shown here: Notice that the output of each of these inverse functions is an \(angle\). Exercise \(\PageIndex{1}\) Evaluate \(\sin ^{-1} \left(-1ight)\) \(	an ^{-1} \left(-1ight)\) \(\cos ^{-1} \left(-1ight)\) \(\cos ^{-1} \left(\dfrac{1}{2} ight)\) Answer a) \(-\dfrac{\pi }{2}\) b) \(-\dfrac{\pi }{4}\) c) \(\pi\) d) \(\dfrac{\pi }{3}\) Exercise Evaluate \(\cos ^{-1} \left(-0.4ight)\) using your calculator. Answer \[1.9823	ext{ or }113.578\mathrm{{}^\circ}
onumber\] In Section 5.5, we worked with trigonometry on a right triangle to solve for the sides of a triangle given one side and an additional angle. Using the inverse trig functions, we can solve for the angles of a right triangle given two sides. There are times when we need to compose a trigonometric function with an inverse trigonometric function. In these cases, we can find exact values for the resulting expressions Exercise \(\PageIndex{3}\) Evaluate \(\cos ^{-1} \left(\sin \left(-\dfrac{11\pi }{4} ight)ight)\). Answer \[\sin \left(-\dfrac{11\pi }{4} ight)=-\dfrac{\sqrt{2} }{2} . \cos ^{-1} \left(-\dfrac{\sqrt{2} }{2} ight)=\dfrac{3\pi }{4} 
onumber\] Exercise \(\PageIndex{4}\) Evaluate \(\cos \left(\sin ^{-1} \left(\dfrac{7}{9} ight)ight)\). Answer Let \(	heta =\sin ^{-1} \left(\dfrac{7}{9} ight)\) so \[\sin (	heta )=\dfrac{7}{9}
onumber\] Using Pythagorean Identity, \(\sin ^{2} 	heta +\cos ^{2} 	heta =1\), so \[\left(\dfrac{7}{9} ight)^{2} +\cos ^{2} 	heta =1
onumber\] Solving, \[\cos \left(\sin ^{-1} \left(\dfrac{7}{9} ight)ight)=\cos \left(	heta ight)=\dfrac{4\sqrt{2} }{9}
onumber\] We can also find compositions involving algebraic expressions Exercise \(\PageIndex{5}\) Find a simplified expression for \(\sin \left(	an ^{-1} \left(4xight)ight)\), for \(-\dfrac{1}{4} \le x\le \dfrac{1}{4}\). Answer Let \(	heta =	an ^{-1} \left(4xight)\), so \(	an (	heta )=4x\). We can represent this on a triangle as \(	an (	heta )=\dfrac{4x}{1}\). The hypotenuse of the triangle would be \(\sqrt{\left(4xight)^{2} +1}\). \[\sin \left(	an ^{-1} \left(4xight)ight)=\sin (	heta )=\dfrac{4x}{\sqrt{16x^{2} +1} }
onumber\] Important Topics of This Section Inverse trig functions: arcsine, arccosine and arctangent Domain restrictions Evaluating inverses using unit circle values and the calculator Simplifying numerical expressions involving the inverse trig functions Simplifying algebraic expressions involving the inverse trig functions

